body:
I'm not 100% the PDFBOX guys got the issue straight :)

Transitivity of comparison operators is not a matter of complying to Comparator/Comparable contracts or some other java technicality... comparison operators _must_ be transitive because otherwise there is no ordering (in the math sense) to begin with.

Here's another test case that (I hope) will shed light on the issue

``` java
@Test
public void testWellDefinedComparison1() {
	Rectangle a = new Rectangle(2,0,2,2);
	Rectangle b = new Rectangle(1,1,2,2);
	Rectangle c = new Rectangle(0,2,2,2);
	List<Rectangle> l1 = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList(b, a, c));
	List<Rectangle> l2 = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList(c, b, a));
	QuickSort.sort(l1);
	QuickSort.sort(l2);
	// At this point l1 and l2 should be the same...
	// I mean, that's kinda the whole purpose of sorting, right?
	// Let's check!
	assertEquals(l1.get(0), l2.get(0));
	assertEquals(l1.get(1), l2.get(1));
	assertEquals(l1.get(2), l2.get(2));
}
```

This is what I get
```
java.lang.AssertionError: expected:<technology.tabula.Rectangle[x=2.0,y=0.0,w=2.0,h=2.0,bottom=2.000000,right=4.000000]> 
                           but was:<technology.tabula.Rectangle[x=0.0,y=2.0,w=2.0,h=2.0,bottom=4.000000,right=2.000000]>
```

PS:
Yes, I had to fiddle with the initial sorting of the two lists – that's why they are not a,b,c/c,b,a – to find a configuration that didn't work.
Please not that there is no issue in QuickSort (AFAIK): the existence of a well define order is a prerequisite for any sorting algorithm.

Well, it isn't really a problem that there are many possible ordering of rectangles in a 2D plane... after all, integers can be ordered in many ways too: low-to-high, high-to-low or (eg) comparing according to values modulo 10 (to get equivalence classes like  {...,0,10,20,..} < {...,1,11,21,...} < {...,2,12,22,...} etc).

The issue is that the specific comparison operator implemented in `Rectangle.compareTo()` does not define a total ordering of rectangles. It's not like it's impossible to define a total order in 2D (eg: "top-to-bottom then left-to-right" is perfectly ok); the issue resides in the idea that a well-defined order can be preserved when different quantities are considered equal if they fall within a certain "tolerance" (because a tolerance does not create an equivalence class).

Consider floats (in 1D):

``` java
public class Tolerant implements Comparator<Float> {

    private static final float TOLERANCE = .5f;

    @Override public int compare(Float f1, Float f2) {
        return Math.abs(f1 - f2) <= TOLERANCE
             ? 0
             : f1.compareTo(f2);
    }
}
```
Is `{ 1, 1.2, 1.4, 1.6, 1.8, 2 }` already sorted according to the Tolerant comparator?
And is `{ 1, 1.4, 1.6, 2, 1.2, 1.8 }` already sorted?

What is the expected result of sorting `{ 2, 1, 1.4, 1.6, 1.2, 1.8, }`?

I wouldn't know what to replace the current (ill-defined) order with... I guess it will depend from case to case?
Maybe in some cases the call to `sort()` can be replaced with things that aren't a sorting algorithm... one would need to know the intentions behind the various calls to `sort()` in order to say.
